Strings in Java are immutable, which means once a String object is created, its value cannot be changed.

String s = "Hello";
s.concat("aashi");-->Java creates a new String object
-->The original "Hello" is still untouched.
System.out.println(s);
o/p--> is still "hello"

String s = "Hello";
s = s.concat("aashi"); --->Make s point to the newly created String
-->You're changing the reference variable s, not the String object.
System.out.println(s);
o/p--> is "hello aashi"

Q.Why did Java make Strings immutable?
-->1. Security
  Strings are used for:

username
password
database URL
file paths
network connections

If Strings were mutable, one piece of code could change them unexpectedly.

2.String Pool Optimization:
Java stores string literals in a special memory area called the String Pool.
String a = "aashi";
String b = "aashi";
Both variables point to the same object.

a ----\
       > "aashi"
b ----/
This saves memory.
If Strings were mutable:
a = "aashi";
could accidentally affect b too.
Immutability prevents this problem.

3.Thread Safety:
Suppose two threads use the same string:
String message = "Welcome";
Since it cannot change, multiple threads can safely use it without synchronization.

4.HashMap Performance
Strings are often used as keys:
HashMap<String, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();
The hash value of a String is cached.
If Strings could change, the hash would change and HashMap lookups could break.


Strings are immutable in Java to provide security, enable String Pool memory optimization, ensure thread safety, 
and allow efficient hashing for collections like HashMap. 
Any modification creates a new String object instead of changing the existing one.
